Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and thinly sliced into half moons). Roughly chop the @coriander{10}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Chop the @sweet potato{1}(chopped into 1cm chunks, no need to peel!). Chop the @whiting fillet{4}(chopped into 2cm pieces).

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} over medium heat. Add the shallot and sweet potato. Cook for ~{3%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Add half the @Pasanda Style Seasoning{1%container} and cook for another ~{2%minutes}. Add the @water for the Curry{200} and the @vegetable stock powder{1/2}. Stir to dissolve the stock pot and leave to simmer until the sweet potato is tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

While the curry is cooking, put a #frying pan{} on medium heat (no oil) add the @desiccated coconut{25%g} and toast until golden, ~{3%minutes}. Stir frequently and be careful - it burns easily. When done, transfer to a #bowl{} and wipe the pan clean with some @kitchen paper{} - we'll use it again in a minute. Put the tilapia pieces in a #mixing bowl{} and add a pinch of @salt{} and the remaining pasanda spice blend. Rub the flavours into the fish.

Return the now empty frying pan to high heat (no oil). When hot, lay in a @super soft tortilla with whole wheat{4}. Cook until slightly scorched, ~{1-2%minutes} per side. When done, transfer to a #plate{}, drizzle over some @oil{} and sprinkle on a few @nigella seeds{1}. Cover with #foil{} to keep warm while you repeat with the remaining tortillas.

When the sweet potato is soft enough to eat, add the @baby spinach{125} to the curry. Stir to combine and cook until the spinach is wilted, ~{3%minutes}. Next, add the @Double Cream{150} and @whiting fillet{4}. Cover the pan with a #lid{} (or some foil) and simmer until the fish is cooked through, another ~{5-6%minutes}. Important: The fish is cooked when the centre is opaque.

When the fish is cooked, add a squeeze of @lime{1}(juice squeezed) and the coriander to the curry. Stir gently (you don't want to break up the fish!), taste and add more salt and lime juice if desired. Finish with a sprinkling of the coconut and any remaining nigella seeds. Serve in deep bowls and mop up the sauce with your chapatis. Enjoy!

> André wanted you to enjoy this delicious creamy curry with some chapatis, but he didn't think everyone would be in the mood for making their own Indian-style flatbreads after a busy day. So, he came up with this cheat's version: whole wheat soft tortillas, warmed in a pan and flavoured with nigella seeds. We think you'll be impressed!